# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: calendar-heatmaps
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] It is also a part of the discipline of history including earth history, the earth sciences, and study of the geologic time scale.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] Chronology is the science of locating historical events in time.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] It relies mostly upon chronometry, which is also known as timekeeping, and historiography, which examines the writing of history and the use of historical methods.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] Radiocarbon dating estimates the age of formerly living things by measuring the proportion of carbon-14 isotope in their carbon content.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] Dendrochronology estimates the age of trees by correlation of the various growth rings in their wood to known year-by-year reference sequences in the region to reflect year-to-year climatic variation.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] Dendrochronology is used in turn as a calibration reference for radiocarbon dating curves.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] The familiar terms *calendar* and *era* (within the meaning of a coherent system of numbered calendar years) concern two complementary fundamental concepts of chronology.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] For example, during eight centuries the calendar belonging to the Christian era, which era was taken in use in the 8th century by Bede, was the Julian calendar, but after the year 1582 it was the Gregorian calendar.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] Dionysius Exiguus (about the year 500) was the founder of that era, which is nowadays the most widespread dating system on earth.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] An epoch is the date (year usually) when an era begins.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] It was used systematically for the first time only about the year 400, by the Iberian historian Orosius.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] Pope Boniface IV, in about the year 600, seems to have been the first who made a connection between this era and Anno Domini.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] Dionysius Exiguus' Anno Domini era (which contains only calendar years *AD*) was extended by Bede to the complete Christian era (which contains, in addition all calendar years *BC*, but no *year zero*).
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] While of critical importance to the historian, methods of determining chronology are used in most disciplines of science, especially astronomy, geology, paleontology and archaeology.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] In the absence of written history, with its chronicles and king lists, late 19th century archaeologists found that they could develop relative chronologies based on pottery techniques and styles.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] In the field of Egyptology, William Flinders Petrie pioneered sequence dating to penetrate pre-dynastic Neolithic times, using groups of contemporary artefacts deposited together at a single time in graves and working backwards methodically from the earliest historical phases of Egypt.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] This method of dating is known as seriation.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] Known wares discovered at strata in sometimes quite distant sites, the product of trade, helped extend the network of chronologies.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] Some cultures have retained the name applied to them in reference to characteristic forms, for lack of an idea of what they called themselves: "The Beaker People" in northern Europe during the 3rd millennium BCE, for example.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] Laboratory techniques developed particularly after mid-20th century helped constantly revise and refine the chronologies developed for specific cultural areas.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] Unrelated dating methods help reinforce a chronology, an axiom of corroborative evidence.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] Ideally, archaeological materials used for dating a site should complement each other and provide a means of cross-checking.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] Conclusions drawn from just one unsupported technique are usually regarded as unreliable.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] The fundamental problem of chronology is to synchronize events.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] By synchronizing an event it becomes possible to relate it to the current time and to compare the event to other events.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] Among historians, a typical need is to synchronize the reigns of kings and leaders in order to relate the history of one country or region to that of another.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] For example, the Chronicon of Eusebius (325 A.D.) is one of the major works of historical synchronism.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] The first contains narrative chronicles of nine different kingdoms: Chaldean, Assyrian, Median, Lydian, Persian, Hebrew, Greek, Peloponnesian, Asian, and Roman.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] The second part is a long table synchronizing the events from each of the nine kingdoms in parallel columns.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] By comparing the parallel columns, the reader can determine which events were contemporaneous, or how many years separated two different events.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] To place all the events on the same time scale, Eusebius used an Anno Mundi (A.M.) era, meaning that events were dated from the supposed beginning of the world as computed from the Book of Genesis in the Hebrew Pentateuch.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] According to the computation Eusebius used, this occurred in 5199 B.C.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] The Chronicon of Eusebius was widely used in the medieval world to establish the dates and times of historical events.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] Subsequent chronographers, such as George Syncellus (died circa 811), analyzed and elaborated on the Chronicon by comparing with other chronologies.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] The last great chronographer was Joseph Justus Scaliger (1540-1609) who reconstructed the lost Chronicon and synchronized all of ancient history in his two major works, *De emendatione temporum* (1583) and *Thesaurus temporum* (1606).
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] Much of modern historical datings and chronology of the ancient world ultimately derives from these two works.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] Scaliger invented the concept of the Julian Day which is still used as the standard unified scale of time for both historians and astronomers.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] In addition to the literary methods of synchronism used by traditional chronographers such as Eusebius, Syncellus and Scaliger, it is possible to synchronize events by archaeological or astronomical means.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] For example, the Eclipse of Thales, described in the first book of Herodotus can potentially be used to date the Lydian War because the eclipse took place during the middle of an important battle in that war.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] Likewise, various eclipses and other astronomical events described in ancient records can be used to astronomically synchronize historical events.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/chronology] Another method to synchronize events is the use of archaeological findings, such as pottery, to do sequence dating.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/color-gradient] In color science, a **color gradient** (also known as a **color ramp** or a **color progression**) specifies a range of position-dependent colors, usually used to fill a region.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/color-gradient] In assigning colors to a set of values, a gradient is a continuous colormap, a type of color scheme.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/color-gradient] In computer graphics, the term swatch has come to mean a palette of active colors.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/color-gradient] An axial color gradient (sometimes also called a linear color gradient) is specified by two points, and a color at each point.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/color-gradient] The colors along the line through those points are calculated using linear interpolation, then extended perpendicular to that line.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/color-gradient] In digital imaging systems, colors are typically interpolated in an RGB color space, often using gamma compressed RGB color values, as opposed to linear.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/color-gradient] CSS and SVG both support linear gradients.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/color-gradient] A radial gradient is specified as a circle that has one color at the edge and another at the center.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/color-gradient] Colors are calculated by linear interpolation based on distance from the center.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/color-gradient] This can be used to approximate the diffuse reflection of light from a point source by a sphere.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/color-gradient] Both CSS and SVG support radial gradients.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/color-gradient] Conic or conical gradients are gradients with color transitions rotated around a center point (rather than radiating from the center).
[src:calendar-heatmaps/color-gradient] Example conic gradients include pie charts and color wheels.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/color-gradient] Conic gradients are sometimes called "sweep gradients" (for example in the OpenType specification) or angular gradients.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/color-gradient] In vector graphics polygon meshes can be used, e.g., Adobe Illustrator supports *gradient meshes*.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/color-gradient] The appearance of a gradient not only varies by the color themselves, but also by the color space the calculation is performed in.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/color-gradient] A "linear" blend would match physical light blending and has been the standard in game engines for a long time.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/color-gradient] On the web, however, it has long been neglected for both color gradients and image scaling.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/color-gradient] Such a blend still has a subtle difference from one done in a perceptually-uniform color space.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/data-binning] In digital image processing, "binning" has a very different meaning.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/data-binning] Pixel binning is the process of combining blocks of adjacent pixels throughout an image, by summing or averaging their values, during or after readout.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/data-binning] It reduces the amount of data; also the relative noise level in the result is lower.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/data-binning] Histograms are an example of data binning used in order to observe underlying frequency distributions.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/data-binning] They typically occur in one-dimensional space and in equal intervals for ease of visualization.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/data-binning] A straightforward way to cope with this problem is by using binning techniques in which the spectrum is reduced in resolution to a sufficient degree to ensure that a given peak remains in its bin despite small spectral shifts between analyses.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/data-binning] For example, in NMR the chemical shift axis may be discretized and coarsely binned, and in MS the spectral accuracies may be rounded to an integer multiple of the dalton.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/data-binning] Also, several digital camera systems incorporate an automatic pixel binning function to improve image contrast.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/data-binning] Binning is also used in machine learning to speed up the decision-tree boosting method for supervised classification and regression in algorithms such as Microsoft's LightGBM and scikit-learn's Histogram-based Gradient Boosting Classification Tree.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] A **heat map** (or **heatmap**) is a two-dimensional data visualization technique that represents the magnitude of individual values within a dataset as a color.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] The variation in color may be by hue or intensity.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] In some applications such as crime analytics or website click-tracking, color is used to represent the *density* of data points rather than a value associated with each point.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] "Heat map" is a relatively new term, but the practice of shading matrices has existed for over a century.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Heat maps originated in 2D displays of the values in a data matrix.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Larger values were represented by small dark gray or black squares (pixels) and smaller values by lighter squares.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] The earliest known example dates to 1873, when Toussaint Loua used a hand-drawn and colored shaded matrix to visualize social statistics across the districts of Paris.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] The idea of reordering rows and columns to reveal structure in a data matrix, known as seriation, was introduced by Flinders Petrie in 1899.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] In 1950, Louis Guttman developed the Scalogram, a method for ordering binary matrices to expose a one-dimensional scale structure.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] In 1957, Peter Sneath displayed the results of a cluster analysis by permuting the rows and the columns of a matrix to place similar values near each other according to the clustering.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] This idea was implemented by Robert Ling in 1973 with a computer program called SHADE.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Ling used overstruck printer characters to represent different shades of gray, one character-width per pixel.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Leland Wilkinson developed the first computer program in 1994 (SYSTAT) to produce cluster heat maps with high-resolution color graphics.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] The Eisen et al. display shown in the figure is a replication of the earlier SYSTAT design.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Software designer Cormac Kinney trademarked the term 'heat map' in 1991 to describe computer software used to display real-time financial market information.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] In 1998 the trademark was acquired by SS&C Technologies, Inc., but the company did not extend the license, so it was annulled in 2006.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] There are two primary categories of heat maps: spatial and grid.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Additionally, there are over ten various types of heat maps.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] A **spatial heat map** displays the magnitude of a spatial phenomenon as color, usually cast over a map.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] In the image labeled "Spatial Heat Map Example," temperature is displayed by color range across a map of the world.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Color ranges from blue (cold) to red (hot).
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] A **grid heat map** displays magnitude as color in a two-dimensional matrix, with each dimension representing a category of trait and the color representing the magnitude of some measurement on the combined traits from each of the two categories.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] For example, one dimension might represent year, and the other dimension might represent month, and the value measured might be temperature.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] This heat map would show how temperature changed over the years in each month.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Grid heat maps are further categorized into two different types of matrices: clustered, and correlogram.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] In a grid heat map, colors are presented in a grid of a fixed size, with every cell in the grid also being an equal size and shape.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] The goal is to detect clustering, or suggest the presence of clusters.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] A spatial heat map is often used on maps or satellite imagery (see GIS), where there is no concept of cells, and instead the colors vary continuously.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Heat maps have a wide range of possibilities amongst applications due to their ability to simplify data and make for visually appealing to read data analysis.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Many applications using different types of heat maps are listed below.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Business Analysis: Heat maps are used in business analytics to give a visual representation about a company's current functioning, performance, and the need for improvements.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Heat maps are a way to analyze a company's existing data and update it to reflect growth and other specific efforts.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Heat maps visually appeal to team members and clients of the business or company.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Websites: There are many different ways heat maps are used within websites to determine a visiting users actions.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Typically, there are multiple heat maps used together to determine insight to a website on what are the best and worst performing elements on the page.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Some specific heat maps used for website analysis are listed below.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Exploratory Data Analysis: Working with small and large data sets, data scientists and data analysts look at and determine essential relationships and characteristics amongst different points in a data set as well as features of those data points.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Data scientists and analysts work with a team of others in different professions.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] The use of heat maps make for a visually easy way to summarize findings and main components.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] There are other ways to represent data, however heat maps can visualize these data points and their relationships in a high dimensional space without becoming too compact and visually unappealing.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Heat maps in data analysis, allow for specific variables of rows and/or columns on the axes and even on the diagonal.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Biology: In the biological field, heat maps are used to visually represent large and small sets of data.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] The focus is towards patterns and similarities in DNA, RNA, gene expression, etc.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Financial Analysis: The values of different product and assets fluctuate both rapidly and/or gradually over time.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] The need to log changes to the daily markets is imperative.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] It allows for the ability to draw predictions from patterns while being able to revisit past numerical data.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Heat maps are able to remove the tedious process and enable the user to visualize data points and compare amongst the different performers.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Geographical Visualization: Heat maps are used to visualize and display a geographic distribution of data.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Heat maps represent different densities of data points on a geographical map to help users see the intensities of certain phenomena and to show items of most or least importance.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Heat maps used in geographical visualization are sometimes confused with choropleth maps, but the difference comes with how certain data is presented which differentiate the two.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Sports: Heat maps can be used in many sports and can influence manager's and/or coaches decisions based on high and low densities of data displayed.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Users can identify patterns within the game, the strategies of opponents and one's own team, make more informed decisions benefitting the player, team, and business, and can enhance performance in different areas by identifying enhancement is needed.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Heat maps also visualize comparisons and relationships amongst different teams in the same sport or between different sports all together.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Cybersecurity: In intrusion detection systems and log analysis, heat maps are used to highlight unusual access patterns, port scanning attempts, and malicious IP clustering.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] They help SOC (Security Operations Center) analysts quickly spot anomalies in large datasets.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Urban Planning: Heat maps are used in urban planning to visualize traffic congestion, pedestrian flow, and environmental conditions for data-driven infrastructure development (Batty et al., 2012).
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Environmental heat maps track air quality and urban heat islands, guiding green space planning (EEA, 2021).
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Noise pollution heat maps aid zoning and mitigation near residential areas (EEA, 2020).
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Commercial planners use foot traffic heat maps to optimize retail layouts (SmartSantander, 2014).
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Integrated in smart city systems, these maps enhance livability, sustainability, and safety (Batty et al., 2012).
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Many different color schemes can be used to illustrate the heat map, with perceptual advantages and disadvantages for each.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Choosing a good color scheme is integral to accurately and effectively displaying data, whereas a poor color scheme can lead viewers to inaccurate conclusions or exclude those with color deficiencies from proper analysis of said data.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Rainbow color maps, while a common choice, suffer from both accessibility and data continuity concerns.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Rainbow maps pose a challenge for users with color vision deficiencies, particularly in those with issues distinguishing red and green – a condition affecting a significant portion of the population.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] In addition to accessibility issues, rainbow heat map colors are not perceptually uniform; equal increments in data values do not correspond to equal changes in color.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] The lack of uniformity can create misleading visual effects, like an artificial boundary or gradient.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] These effects can compromise the accuracy of effectiveness of the visualization.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] This example of the amplitude with the colors showcasing the phase angle can be hard to interpret with the entire rainbow of colors.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] In this case, the rainbow color scheme may cloud interpretation for those with color vision deficiencies or create confusion by some of the hard color boundaries across the diagram.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] To address these challenges, perceptually uniform color sets have been created to accommodate visual impairments and maintain consistent color differences proportional to differences in data.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Perceptually uniform color schemes are carefully designed to maintain consistent perceptual differences and offer a better viewing experience for viewers with color vision deficiencies.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] When implementing these color schemes into a heat map, designers must consider the data context and intended emphasis.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] These schemes follow three main patterns: sequential gradients (varying intensity of a single hue), diverging palettes (two contrasting hues with a neutral midpoint), and qualitative sets for categorical data.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Scientific visualization has produced several perceptually uniform color sets (like Viridis, Magma, and Cividis) that address both uniformity and accessibility concerns.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Device limitations can also significantly affect heat map visualization effectiveness.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] When displayed on low-resolution screens, highly detailed color gradients may appear pixelated or banded, reducing the quality of the visualization; this is known as color quantization, which can obscure or wrongly emphasize pieces of data.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] To mitigate these effects, designers should consider all devices that will display their heat map, and their color limitations.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Comprehensive testing and using a scheme with few colors is the safest bet when creating a heat map that will be viewed across multiple device types.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Grey-scale compatibility is essential for heat map accessibility, especially when considering print media, black and white only displays, or monochromatic vision.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] When converting to grey-scale, many color schemes will lose their distinctive data mappings, allowing for different values to appear identical in luminescence.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Grey-scale friendly color schemes are designed to incorporate contrast between data points even when color is removed, such as the "virdis" family.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Choropleth maps and heat maps are often used in place of one another incorrectly when referring to data visualized geographically.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Both techniques show the proportion of a variable of interest, but the two differ in how the boundaries for the variable's data aggregations are constructed.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] If the data were collected and aggregated using irregular boundaries, such as administrative units, then a heat map displaying that data will be the same as a choropleth map, encouraging confusion about how the two differ.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Choropleth maps show data grouped by geographic boundaries like countries, states, provinces or even floodplains.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Each region has a singular value, visualized by color intensity, shading or pattern.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] The figure on the right displaying a choropleth map showing the United States' population density by state may be used as an example.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] The figure illustrates a singular value (population) denoted by blue color intensity proportionate to the state's value relative to all other states' values, bounded by each state's border.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Similarly, heat maps may also visualize data over a geographic region.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] However, unlike choropleth maps, heat maps show the proportion of a variable over an arbitrary, but usually small grid size, independent of geographic boundaries.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] The figure on the right displaying a heat map of world population is an example.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] The figure illustrates a single value (population) bounded in an arbitrary grid (square kilometers) with each cell in the grid represented by a color intensity proportionate to the value of the cell relative to all other cells.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Some heat maps that are created using approximated regional data may show familiar geographic borders in the visualization where none really exist.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] The illusion of geographic borders is due to the existence of patterns within the dataset rather than the visualization technique.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] The figure on the right displaying a heat map of world population also contains this occurrence.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Areas in rural parts of the United States and South America may closely resemble familiar geographic borders in those regions.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] Another example of a heatmap over a geographic area is a visualization of lake effect snow around Buffalo, New York, in mid-October 2006.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/heat-map] This figure shows another usage of heat maps with geographic areas, and how useful they can be in showcasing the effects of weather on specific areas as opposed to countries or states.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/small-multiple] A **small multiple** (sometimes called **trellis chart**, **lattice chart**, **grid chart**, or **panel chart**) is a series of similar graphs or charts using the same scale and axes, allowing them to be easily compared.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/small-multiple] It uses multiple views to show different partitions of a dataset.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/small-multiple] The term was popularized by Edward Tufte.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/small-multiple] In the example, the departmental salary expense is charted by month with a dashed line indicating the average for each department.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/small-multiple] The scales on each panel are different to emphasize the relative change over time compared to the range.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/small-multiple] Standardizing the scales could provide insight into comparisons in magnitude between the different departments.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/small-multiple] Two independent Y axes may be utilized when presenting data with different numeric scales in each panel.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/small-multiple] Muybridge's work not only proved for the first time that all four of a horse's hooves left the ground during gallop (see upper central plates), but it also broke new ground in terms of artistic expression and became foundational to the development of the motion picture.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/small-multiple] Muybridge went on to produce many more examples of small multiples showing animal locomotion through the medium of stop-motion photography, including boys playing leapfrog and a bison cantering.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/small-multiple] Adjacent is a chart showing the population broken down by occupation, including a count of those attending school, according to the 1870 Census.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/small-multiple] This graphic is innovative in its use of both a treemap display and a latticed layout of small multiples.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/small-multiple] Additional examples appearing in the *Atlas* include side-by-side geographic maps showing the changes in population over time, as well as tiled mosaic charts showing population demographic breakdowns, and diverging bar graphs showing deaths broken down by age and gender, tiled by state.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/small-multiple] Small multiples are a popular technique in cartographic design for multivariate mapping.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/small-multiple] As with the small multiple chart, each panel uses the same underlying two-dimensional space, but in this case that is a geographic space.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/small-multiple] Typically, the variables being mapped are of a similar type, such as types of agricultural products, so that the same strategy of map symbol can be used on each panel, enabling rapid comparison between the maps.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/small-multiple] Another common use of small multiples is to show change in spatial patterns over time, as an alternative to an animated map.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/small-multiple] Several tests of the effectiveness of each method have generally concluded that they have distinct advantages, with animation being better for seeing trends, especially movement, and small multiples being better for making comparisons between times.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] In mathematics, a **time series** is a sequence of data points indexed, listed, or graphed in chronological order.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Most commonly, a time series consists of observations recorded at successive equally spaced points in time.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Thus, it represents a form of discrete-time data.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] A time series may describe measurements collected over seconds, days, years, or even centuries.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Common examples include heights of ocean tides, counts of sunspots, daily temperature readings, and the closing values of stock market indices such as the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] A time series is often visualized using a run chart (a type of temporal line chart), which helps identify patterns such as trends, seasonal effects, and irregular fluctuations.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Time series data have a natural temporal ordering.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] This makes time series analysis distinct from cross-sectional studies, in which there is no natural ordering of the observations (e.g. explaining people's wages by reference to their respective education levels, where the individuals' data could be entered in any order).
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Time series analysis is also distinct from spatial data analysis where the observations typically relate to geographical locations (e.g. accounting for house prices by the location as well as the intrinsic characteristics of the houses).
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] A stochastic model for a time series will generally reflect the fact that observations close together in time will be more closely related than observations further apart.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] In addition, time series models will often make use of the natural one-way ordering of time so that values for a given period will be expressed as deriving in some way from past values, rather than from future values (see time reversibility).
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Time series analysis can be applied to real-valued, continuous data, discrete numeric data, or discrete symbolic data (i.e. sequences of characters, such as letters and words in the English language).
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Methods for time series analysis may be divided into two classes: frequency-domain methods and time-domain methods.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] The former include spectral analysis and wavelet analysis; the latter include auto-correlation and cross-correlation analysis.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] In the time domain, correlation and analysis can be made in a filter-like manner using scaled correlation, thereby mitigating the need to operate in the frequency domain.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Additionally, time series analysis techniques may be divided into parametric and non-parametric methods.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] The parametric approaches assume that the underlying stationary stochastic process has a certain structure which can be described using a small number of parameters (for example, using an autoregressive or moving-average model).
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] In these approaches, the task is to estimate the parameters of the model that describes the stochastic process.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] By contrast, non-parametric approaches explicitly estimate the covariance or the spectrum of the process without assuming that the process has any particular structure.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Methods of time series analysis may also be divided into linear and non-linear, and univariate and multivariate.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] A time series is one type of panel data.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Panel data is the general class, a multidimensional data set, whereas a time series data set is a one-dimensional panel (as is a cross-sectional dataset).
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] A data set may exhibit characteristics of both panel data and time series data.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] One way to tell is to ask what makes one data record unique from the other records.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] If the answer is the time data field, then this is a time series data set candidate.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] If determining a unique record requires a time data field and an additional identifier which is unrelated to time (e.g. student ID, stock symbol, country code), then it is panel data candidate.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] If the differentiation lies on the non-time identifier, then the data set is a cross-sectional data set candidate.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] There are several types of motivation and data analysis available for time series which are appropriate for different purposes.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] In the context of statistics, econometrics, quantitative finance, seismology, meteorology, and geophysics the primary goal of time series analysis is forecasting.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] In the context of signal processing, control engineering and communication engineering it is used for signal detection.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Other applications are in data mining, pattern recognition and machine learning, where time series analysis can be used for clustering, classification, query by content, anomaly detection as well as forecasting.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] A simple way to examine a regular time series is manually with a line chart.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] The datagraphic shows tuberculosis deaths in the United States, along with the yearly change and the percentage change from year to year.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] The total number of deaths declined in every year until the mid-1980s, after which there were occasional increases, often proportionately - but not absolutely - quite large.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] A study of corporate data analysts found two challenges to exploratory time series analysis: discovering the shape of interesting patterns, and finding an explanation for these patterns.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Visual tools that represent time series data as heat map matrices can help overcome these challenges.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] This approach may be based on harmonic analysis and filtering of signals in the frequency domain using the Fourier transform, and spectral density estimation.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Its development was significantly accelerated during World War II by mathematician Norbert Wiener, electrical engineers Rudolf E.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Kálmán, Dennis Gabor and others for filtering signals from noise and predicting signal values at a certain point in time.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] An equivalent effect may be achieved in the time domain, as in a Kalman filter; see filtering and smoothing for more techniques.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Curve fitting is the process of constructing a curve, or mathematical function, that has the best fit to a series of data points, possibly subject to constraints.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Curve fitting can involve either interpolation, where an exact fit to the data is required, or smoothing, in which a "smooth" function is constructed that approximately fits the data.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] A related topic is regression analysis, which focuses more on questions of statistical inference such as how much uncertainty is present in a curve that is fit to data observed with random errors.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Fitted curves can be used as an aid for data visualization, to infer values of a function where no data are available, and to summarize the relationships among two or more variables.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Extrapolation refers to the use of a fitted curve beyond the range of the observed data, and is subject to a degree of uncertainty since it may reflect the method used to construct the curve as much as it reflects the observed data.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] For processes that are expected to generally grow in magnitude one of the curves in the graphic (and many others) can be fitted by estimating their parameters.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] The construction of economic time series involves the estimation of some components for some dates by interpolation between values ("benchmarks") for earlier and later dates.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Interpolation is estimation of an unknown quantity between two known quantities (historical data), or drawing conclusions about missing information from the available information ("reading between the lines").
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Interpolation is useful where the data surrounding the missing data is available and its trend, seasonality, and longer-term cycles are known.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] This is often done by using a related series known for all relevant dates.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Alternatively polynomial interpolation or spline interpolation is used where piecewise polynomial functions are fitted in time intervals such that they fit smoothly together.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] A different problem which is closely related to interpolation is the approximation of a complicated function by a simple function (also called regression).
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] The main difference between regression and interpolation is that polynomial regression gives a single polynomial that models the entire data set.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Spline interpolation, however, yield a piecewise continuous function composed of many polynomials to model the data set.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Extrapolation is the process of estimating, beyond the original observation range, the value of a variable on the basis of its relationship with another variable.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] It is similar to interpolation, which produces estimates between known observations, but extrapolation is subject to greater uncertainty and a higher risk of producing meaningless results.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] In general, a function approximation problem asks us to select a function among a well-defined class that closely matches ("approximates") a target function in a task-specific way.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Second, the target function, call it *g*, may be unknown; instead of an explicit formula, only a set of points (a time series) of the form (*x*, *g*(*x*)) is provided.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Depending on the structure of the domain and codomain of *g*, several techniques for approximating *g* may be applicable.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] For example, if *g* is an operation on the real numbers, techniques of interpolation, extrapolation, regression analysis, and curve fitting can be used.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] If the codomain (range or target set) of *g* is a finite set, one is dealing with a classification problem instead.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] A related problem of *online* time series approximation is to summarize the data in one-pass and construct an approximate representation that can support a variety of time series queries with bounds on worst-case error.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] To some extent, the different problems (regression, classification, fitness approximation) have received a unified treatment in statistical learning theory, where they are viewed as supervised learning problems.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] In statistics, prediction is a part of statistical inference.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] One particular approach to such inference is known as predictive inference, but the prediction can be undertaken within any of the several approaches to statistical inference.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Indeed, one description of statistics is that it provides a means of transferring knowledge about a sample of a population to the whole population, and to other related populations, which is not necessarily the same as prediction over time.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] When information is transferred across time, often to specific points in time, the process is known as forecasting.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Assigning time series pattern to a specific category, for example identify a word based on series of hand movements in sign language.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Splitting a time-series into a sequence of segments.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] It is often the case that a time-series can be represented as a sequence of individual segments, each with its own characteristic properties.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] For example, the audio signal from a conference call can be partitioned into pieces corresponding to the times during which each person was speaking.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] In time-series segmentation, the goal is to identify the segment boundary points in the time-series, and to characterize the dynamical properties associated with each segment.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] One can approach this problem using change-point detection, or by modeling the time-series as a more sophisticated system, such as a Markov jump linear system.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Time series data may be clustered, however special care has to be taken when considering subsequence clustering.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Subsequence time series clustering resulted in unstable (random) clusters *induced by the feature extraction* using chunking with sliding windows.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] It was found that the cluster centers (the average of the time series in a cluster - also a time series) follow an arbitrarily shifted sine pattern (regardless of the dataset, even on realizations of a random walk).
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] This means that the found cluster centers are non-descriptive for the dataset because the cluster centers are always nonrepresentative sine waves.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Models for time series data can have many forms and represent different stochastic processes.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] When modeling variations in the level of a process, three broad classes of practical importance are the *autoregressive* (AR) models, the *integrated* (I) models, and the *moving-average* (MA) models.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] These three classes depend *linearly* on previous data points.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Combinations of these ideas produce autoregressive moving-average (ARMA) and autoregressive integrated moving-average (ARIMA) models.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] The autoregressive fractionally integrated moving-average (ARFIMA) model generalizes the former three.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Another important generalization is the time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) model, in which the AR coefficients are allowed to change over time, enabling the model to capture evolving or non-stationary dynamics.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Extensions of these classes to deal with vector-valued data are available under the heading of multivariate time-series models and sometimes the preceding acronyms are extended by including an initial "V" for "vector", as in VAR for vector autoregression.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] For these models, the acronyms are extended with a final "X" for "exogenous".
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) models are especially useful for analyzing non-stationary time series in which the underlying dynamics evolve over time in complex ways, not limited to classical forms of variation such as trends or seasonal patterns.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] This flexibility makes them well suited to modeling structural changes, regime shifts, or gradual evolutions in a system's behavior.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Estimation of TVAR models typically involves methods such as kernel smoothing, recursive least squares, or Kalman filtering.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Non-linear dependence of the level of a series on previous data points is of interest, partly because of the possibility of producing a chaotic time series.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] However, more importantly, empirical investigations can indicate the advantage of using predictions derived from non-linear models, over those from linear models, as for example in nonlinear autoregressive exogenous models.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Among other types of non-linear time series models, there are models to represent the changes of variance over time (heteroskedasticity).
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] These models represent autoregressive conditional heteroskedasticity (ARCH) and the collection comprises a wide variety of representation (GARCH, TARCH, EGARCH, FIGARCH, CGARCH, etc.).
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Here changes in variability are related to, or predicted by, recent past values of the observed series.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] This is in contrast to other possible representations of locally varying variability, where the variability might be modeled as being driven by a separate time-varying process, as in a doubly stochastic model.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Multiscale (often referred to as multiresolution) techniques decompose a given time series, attempting to illustrate time dependence at multiple scales.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] See also Markov switching multifractal (MSMF) techniques for modeling volatility evolution.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] A hidden Markov model (HMM) is a statistical Markov model in which the system being modeled is assumed to be a Markov process with unobserved (hidden) states.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] An HMM can be considered as the simplest dynamic Bayesian network.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] HMM models are widely used in speech recognition, for translating a time series of spoken words into text.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Many of these models are collected in the python package sktime.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] A number of different notations are in use for time-series analysis.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Ergodicity implies stationarity, but the converse is not necessarily the case.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Stationarity is usually classified into strict stationarity and wide-sense or second-order stationarity.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Both models and applications can be developed under each of these conditions, although the models in the latter case might be considered as only partly specified.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] In addition, time-series analysis can be applied where the series are seasonally stationary or non-stationary.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Situations where the amplitudes of frequency components change with time can be dealt with in time-frequency analysis which makes use of a time–frequency representation of a time-series or signal.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Time series can be visualized with two categories of chart: Overlapping Charts and Separated Charts.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] Jevons was the first to study times series.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] In his book he examined a number of weekly financial time series between the years 1825 to 1860 inclusive.
[src:calendar-heatmaps/time-series] These included times series of bankruptcies, currency circulation and discount rates.
